title: Part 8
content:
Part 8

IT REPEATED. IT repeated. The day repeated.

The days of learning that seemed to go on forever repeated.

In that world with almost no breaks, we, the fourth-generation students, continued to repeat the curriculum.

There was nothing more to talk about.

No matter how complex or difficult it became, what we had to do didn't change.

Tomorrow, the day after, and the days following, it repeated. It repeated. It repeated.

The next day came as if it were a given.

We learned something new again.

We absorbed it. If we didn't absorb it, we couldn't survive.

Once branded as a dropout, that label couldn't be removed.

And what was normal until the day before wasn't guaranteed to continue from that day on.

The buzzer sounded.

The children placed their pens on the desks in accordance with the rules.

With this, the current high-difficulty written lesson ended.

The exam papers were collected and grading began immediately.

During this time, the children had to sit silently and wait for the results.

Usually, they would know before the results came out.

All the children remaining here knew how many correct answers they got.

In the front row, a small back slightly trembled.

I watched it somewhat absentmindedly as I waited for the moment.

As soon as an instructor entered, he approached the trembling child.

"…You failed."

In front of the child… In front of Yuki, the instructor announced this in his usual indifferent tone.

It decided that another one would fall.

The remaining fourth-generation students had already dwindled to just four, and now, one more seat would disappear.

"This can't be…"

In the White Room, failing during practice and while learning wasn't considered a problem.

The progress up to the exam was meaningless; whether you scored ten points or five points didn't matter. The instructor just continued the lessons without stopping.

Whether you dropped out or not, the regular exams decided everything.

If you couldn't meet the standards here, you would be deemed incapable and dropped.

"Stand up."

These short words, free from impurities, said it all.

"I… don't want to…"

Once you responded to that demand, you were never allowed to live as a White Room student again.

Even if you refused, nothing would change.

Yet, resisting children like Yuki always existed—always.

"I'll say it again. Stand up."

"…Please give me another chance."

Yuki continued to resist with a strained voice, but the instructor looked away and glanced upstairs.

Considering the situation could get out of hand, he must've called for backup.

"S-Sure, I might've been short on points. However, I got through the physical ability lessons the day before. And the points… I was only about five points short. I'll study for next time, I'll definitely make it…!"

Ignoring the pleading Yuki, three new instructors rushed in and entered the room.

If the score she gave herself was accurate, Yuki's score was just five points short of the cutoff point.

To an observer, it might've seemed like a mere five points, but in the White Room, even being one point short meant no salvation.

That was the truth that emerged from nurturing many students.

Children who failed to meet the cutoff point once generally had lower learning abilities afterward.

It had been proven. In other words, even if they turned a blind eye now and overlooked it until the next regular exam, she couldn't avoid being the candidate for the next dropout.

Once you could see the cutoff point, you no longer qualified to remain as a fourth-generation student.

"Rotten oranges must be removed. They only hinder development."

Seems like he doesn't intend to spend more time with her.

One of the instructors reached out to Yuki's arm.

"No, I don't want this!"

As she brushed off the arm and stood up, Yuki, still in disarray, rushed over.

"Help me, Kiyotaka! I don't want to disappear!!"

Yuki sought salvation while her tears overflowed.

While glancing at the slowly approaching instructor, I didn't change my indifferent stance.

"It's impossible."

"…"

I can't help. No, I don't intend to.

"Please! I'll definitely do my best next time! Absolutely!"

"Next time? Why didn't you make an effort before? You should know there's no next time."

"But, that's…!"

Those who couldn't make an effort now wouldn't be able to do so later.

Just as people only had one life, it was impossible for her to continue.

"Still… I can do it…!"

Seems she wants them to consider her past achievements.

The instructors surrounded her along with me.

"Ah!?"

With my gaze, I signaled the approaching instructors to stop and spoke to Yuki.

"Indeed, other than the written exams, you kept up with the curriculum. However, your grades have been declining year by year, and there haven't been any signs of improvement. This is your limit, Yuki—that's what it means."

Even if she were to be rescued, it wasn't a decision for the child being taken away to make, but for the instructor. The very fact that Yuki was clinging to me like this only allowed me to ascertain that her judgment was undoubtedly flawed.

"Come here."

"No! No! Please! Let me try one more time!"

With her voice raised, Yuki showed an unusually strong resistance against her predicament.

It wasn't uncommon for those who were dropping out, but Yuki's behavior was slightly different from previous times.

"You should know the White Room's rules well. Why are you so upset?"

The White Room students, myself included, didn't understand the situation.

However, the instructors thoroughly understood why Yuki was resisting so much.

However, they wouldn't verbalize the reason.

With her arm grabbed, she was forcibly pulled away from me.

"Help me! No! Kiyotaka! Kiyotaka!!"

She called out my name over and over, screaming, seeking help.

"Help, please…!"

As she crumbled and fell, she reached out to me for salvation.

Help?

The girl in front of me had already been declared a failure.

Those who failed had to leave this room.

And they would never return.

There were no exceptions.

So, why did she need to seek help?

It was just a waste of effort, a waste of time.

"Please, I don't want to leave this place!"

Seeing that she refused to leave, two adults hurriedly entered the room.

They restrained the girl and dragged her out.

"No! No! Help me!"

Another person failed to achieve their goal and dropped out.

The remaining children were probably watching with the same detached eyes as mine.

Or maybe they were afraid that they might be next.

Either was fine.

I just needed to be the last one remaining.

I had always relied solely on that feeling to live in this world.

In this white world, I continued to live. Was her cry born from having spent the same years learning together, like family—or perhaps in a completely different dimension, it was a cry born from an affection toward the opposite sex.

Being dragged out from here meant having your entire self denied.

Therefore, everyone repeated their studies within the limited time to avoid that fate.

However—

"Please wait."

I quietly muttered and addressed the instructors.

"Who said you could speak? If you open your mouth without permission next time, you won't get off easy."

"Then I don't need to get off easy. Please listen."

Right after those words, the instructor fell silent, approached me, and kicked without a hint of hesitation.

"You don't have permission to speak."

"Yuki seemed unwell since before noon. She was restless during the test, and perhaps she couldn't demonstrate her abilities due to reasons other than her capabilities—"

As I tried to continue, I was suddenly grabbed by the collar.

"Maintaining your condition is also a part of your capabilities. Do you think such an excuse is valid now? There were no abnormalities observed in the morning."

"That's true. However, if it's something unexpected, the situation changes."

"Unexpected?"

The instructor turned around and looked at the other instructors surrounding the collapsed Yuki.

"There's bleeding."

Having observed her, it seemed the adults realized Yuki's abnormal condition.

"Bleeding? Where did she get injured, or is it that?"

"Yes. Normally, it starts from age nine at the earliest, but it's unusual for it to happen this early. It might be due to the stress caused by the higher level of difficulty compared to other groups. She seems to have a fever as well, so the unexpected health issues are understandable."

"Go to the infirmary. Whether she's failed will be determined after a thorough examination."

With that, the instructor gave the order and took Yuki out of the room.

As she left, crying, Yuki looked at me, but I didn't meet her gaze.

"You noticed well. That's what I'd like to say, but we would've realized it soon after without you pointing it out. Your unauthorized speech is still a problem."

"Then will you punish me?"

Rule violations outside the curriculum were often penalized by things such as corporal punishment.

However, that was it.

I knew they couldn't resort to drastic measures like failing us.

"Are you underestimating me?"

"If you're watching, then observe more carefully."

"You bastard!"

Too late. The instructor, revealing his murderous intent with his right fist clenched, swung at me, but I dodged.

"Stop!"

Another instructor hurried back and stopped the one who was about to overreact.

"Rookie, don't be swayed by a child's words."

"…"

Inexperienced instructors existed, but with this new one, there would likely be more mistakes.

That was why it was necessary to make them aware at this stage.

If they were going to be used, ensure they were more properly educated. If deemed unusable, dispose of them.

However, from that day on, Yuki never returned.
